Weekly Breach Investigation
Breach: ShinyHunters — Oracle PeopleSoft Zero‑Day Exploitation
Analyst: Jamal Mahmoad
Date: 2026-06-12

1. Executive Summary
The ShinyHunters extortion crew exploited a zero‑day flaw (CVE‑2026‑35273) in Oracle PeopleSoft Enterprise PeopleTools to gain remote code execution, steal sensitive data, and extort victims.
The bug (CVSS 9.8) required no login or user interaction, exposing servers with the Environment Management Hub (PSEMHUB) accessible over HTTP.
Universities were hit hardest, with hundreds of thousands of student and alumni records leaked.

2. Attack Timeline

May 27 – June 9, 2026: Active exploitation by ShinyHunters (UNC6240).
June 10, 2026: Oracle publishes advisory after zero‑day window closes.
Exploitation Path:
Vulnerable PeopleSoft endpoints exposed.
Attackers deploy custom MeshCentral agents disguised as Azure binaries.
Lateral movement via SSH spraying with hardcoded credentials.
Marker file dropped: README-IF-YOU-SEE-THIS-YOUVE-BEEN-HACKED.TXT.
Data compressed with zstd and exfiltrated via SSH to ShinyHunters leak servers.

3. MITRE ATT&CK Mapping

Execution: Exploitation for Remote Services (T1190)
Persistence: Web Shell / JSP Injection (T1505)
Privilege Escalation: Abuse of Valid Accounts (T1078)
Defense Evasion: Masquerading (T1036), Obfuscated Files (T1027)
Credential Access: Credential Dumping via SSH spraying (T1110)
Lateral Movement: Remote Services over SSH (T1021.004)
Exfiltration: Exfiltration Over SSH (T1048)
Impact: Data Exposure / Extortion

4. Detection Opportunities

Log Sources:
WebLogic access logs for POST requests to /PSEMHUB/hub or /PSIGW/HttpListeningConnector.
File system changes under PSEMHUB.war (unexpected .jsp files, odd folders).
Recently modified .xml files in envmetadata/data/environment.
Outbound SMB traffic on port 445 from PeopleSoft hosts.
Detection Rules:
Alert on mismatches between DNS resolution and actual endpoints.
Flag unauthorized MeshCentral agents or suspicious binaries.
Monitor for zstd compression followed by outbound SSH connections.

5. Recommended Mitigations

Disable or remove PSEMHUB service/application.
Block external access to /PSEMHUB/* and /PSIGW/HttpListeningConnector.
Apply Oracle’s patch once available in My Oracle Support.
Hunt for persistence via .jsp web shells and modified .xml files.
Restrict outbound SMB and SSH traffic from PeopleSoft servers.

Analyst Notes

This breach highlights the danger of ERP zero‑days in data‑rich environments like universities.
ShinyHunters moved beyond SaaS token theft and vishing into server‑side exploitation, showing a strategic escalation.
The campaign exposed over 455,000 student and alumni records (including sensitive personal data), confirming the severity of the attack.
Whether this is a one‑off borrowed exploit or the start of ShinyHunters targeting ERP systems remains an open question
